The paper proposes a modification to the Support Vector Machine (SVM) algorithm to improve its training time, which is a common problem in machine learning. This modification involves selecting a representative subset of the training dataset and conducting the SVM optimization over this subset. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper applies this modification to datasets related to seizure detection and image classification, which suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. The paper also uses a linear time algorithm based on convex hulls and extreme points, which could place it in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper compares its approach to other SVM methods, indicating that it could also belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
